&lt;p style="text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;S&amp;Atilde;O MARTINHO REPORTS CASH NET INCOME OF R$238.4 MILLION IN 1Q22,&lt;br /&gt;
UP 61.1% ON 1Q21&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p align="center"&gt;&lt;i&gt;The Company reported solid financial results for the first quarter of the 2021/22 crop year&lt;/i&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;S&amp;atilde;o Paulo, August 9, 2021&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ndash; After the start of another crop year, S&amp;atilde;o Martinho reported positive numbers and solid growth in its key financial indicators. The highlight was the Cash Net Income of R$238.4 million in the first quarter of the 2021/22 crop year, representing growth of 61.1% on the same quarter of the prior crop year. Meanwhile, Net Income came to R$190.1 million (+64.3%) in 1Q22.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
From the operational standpoint, the Company processed 8.7 million tons of sugarcane in 1Q22, 12.9% less than in the same period of the previous crop year. The reduction is explained mainly by the drier weather in production regions that has been observed since 2020, and by the fewer days for harvest operations in the first quarter of the crop year at some of mills located in the state of S&amp;atilde;o Paulo, which started at a later date than in 1Q21. However, average Total Recoverable Sugars (TRS) increased 2.9%, leading total TRS produced in the quarter to decline by 10.4%.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Considering its main products, the Company produced around 545,000 tons of sugar (-8,6%), 358,000 m&amp;sup3; of ethanol (-11,9%) and 303,000 MWh of cogeneration sold (-11%). The sugar/ethanol production mix remained stable in relation to the same quarter last crop year, at 48%/52%.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Net revenue amounted to R$1,321.5 million in 1Q22, advancing 28.8% on the same period last crop year, driven primarily by the higher average sales prices for ethanol (+84.7%), sugar (+28.3%) and cogeneration (+24.9%), as well as the sales volume of CBIOS decarbonization credits (~484,000) during the period. This performance contributed to Adjusted EBITDA, which amounted to R$688.3 million in the quarter, representing margin of 52.1% (+4.2 p.p.) and an increase of 40.1% compared to 1Q21.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Another financial indicator, the Company&amp;rsquo;s Financial Leverage (Net Debt/Adjusted EBITDA) stood at 1.02x on June 30, 2021, declining 30.8% from a year earlier.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style="text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;img alt="" src="https://files.workr.com.br/ViewImage.aspx?image=B+xWSCsAYOyuC9UQNmLhFg==" style="width: 350px; height: 233px;" /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style="text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;S&amp;atilde;o Martinho Mill&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
</description><link>https://www.saomartinho.com.br/show.aspx?idMateria=x/1fxevjhnShofYzuRB19A==&amp;linguagem=en</link></item><item><pubDate>Tue, 13 Jul 2021 10:56:00 GMT</pubDate><title>In partnership with Cubo Itaú, São Martinho launches Cubo Agro jointly with other industry companies</title><description>&lt;p align="center"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;IN PARTNERSHIP WITH CUBO ITA&amp;Uacute;, S&amp;Atilde;O MARTINHO LAUNCHES CUBO AGRO JOINTLY WITH OTHER INDUSTRY COMPANIES&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;em&gt;In an unprecedented initiative, S&amp;atilde;o Martinho and partners create Latin America&amp;rsquo;s largest hub for accelerating the technological development of agribusiness startups &lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p align="center"&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;S&amp;atilde;o Paulo, July 13, 2021&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ndash; S&amp;atilde;o Martinho, one of Brazil&amp;rsquo;s largest sugar and ethanol groups, announces its participation in the creation of Cubo Agro, the new vertical of Cubo Ita&amp;uacute; specializing in agribusiness. With the mission of driving technological entrepreneurship through innovation in agribusiness in Brazil and Latin America, Cubo Agro is a new space for connecting agtechs, large businesses, investment funds and other agents in the ecosystem.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style="text-align: justify;"&gt;In partnership with Corteva Agriscience and Ita&amp;uacute; BBA, Cubo Agro is planning an intense agenda of activities to foster the creation of new businesses as well as exchange between startups and other players in this ecosystem through workshops, events for networking and sharing experiences, courses, training and more.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style="text-align: justify;"&gt;To S&amp;atilde;o Martinho, participating in Cubo Agro as co-founder is aligned with its vision of the future and its business strategy in an industry that is constantly adopting more advanced technologies with the potential to make agro-industrial environments increasingly efficient and sustainable. In addition to making an important contribution to fostering the innovation environment, the partnership is yet another opportunity for S&amp;atilde;o Martinho to continue on its journey guided by innovation and sustainability, while leveraging possibilities for new revenue streams by expanding its core business.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style="text-align: justify;"&gt;One of the contributions it expects to make via Cubo Agro is the development of projects based on 5G technology, which offers higher connectivity potential for the agro-industrial environment.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;ldquo;The partnership with Cubo Agro is aligned with our vision of future during a moment marked by major transformations and challenges for Brazilian agribusiness. We believe this environment will play a fundamental role in accelerating and sustaining new business lines for our company, while fostering technological entrepreneurship in the industry and the sharing of experiences and mutual learning with our partners in the initiative as well as other actors in the innovation ecosystem. We&amp;rsquo;re very optimistic on the initiative,&amp;rdquo; said Marcelo Eskenazi, Head of Innovation at S&amp;atilde;o Martinho.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style="text-align: justify;"&gt;To Agenor Pavan, COO and vice-president of S&amp;atilde;o Martinho, Cubo Agro will bring a series of competencies that are complementary to those already amassed by the company over the years. &amp;ldquo;We believe in the concept of open innovation and will learn much from the experience with Cubo Ita&amp;uacute; jointly with the innovation and startup ecosystem. We plan to consolidate our strategy in synergy with the other partners to obtain connections that foster agribusiness and create value sustainably for our company and the entire industry&amp;rdquo;, he added.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style="text-align: justify;"&gt;According to Radar Agtech Brazil 2020/2021, a document developed by Embrapa, SP Ventures and Homo Luders Research and Consulting, almost one agtech per day has been created in Brazil since the onset of the pandemic. The data show 40% more active startups in comparison with Radar Agtech Brasil 2019. The state of S&amp;atilde;o Paulo has the highest percentage of agtechs (48% of the total), while the Northeast region accounts for the largest number of new entrepreneurs in relation to 2019.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style="text-align: justify;"&gt;Another study conducted by the Brazilian Association of Startups (ABStartups) indicates that 72.6% of agtechs work with technologies that support agricultural production and management, while 47.1% of agtechs already have received investments, highlighting the sector&amp;rsquo;s potential.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style="text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;img alt="" src="https://files.workr.com.br/ViewImage.aspx?image=ssj00L4lFwbaOevrYz7vpg==" style="width: 350px; height: 197px;" /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
</description><link>https://www.saomartinho.com.br/show.aspx?idMateria=qtqUGVkA5aG3g/YUwQAuEg==&amp;linguagem=en</link></item><item><pubDate>Thu, 01 Jul 2021 18:14:00 GMT</pubDate><title>São Martinho announces R$ 1 billion financing deal for green projects</title><description>&lt;p style="text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;S&amp;Atilde;O MARTINHO ANNOUNCES R$ 1 BILLION FINANCING DEAL FOR GREEN PROJECTS&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;S&amp;atilde;o Paulo, July 1, 2021 &lt;/strong&gt;&amp;mdash; S&amp;atilde;o Martinho, one of Brazil&amp;rsquo;s largest sugar and energy groups, announces that it successfully carried out a R$ 1 billion funding operation whose proceeds will be used in green projects currently planned by the company. Part of the amount, US$ 100 million, was raised through the International Finance Corporation (IFC) and Rabobank. The remaining R$ 500 million was raised via an infrastructure bond issue managed by Banco Ita&amp;uacute;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style="text-align: justify;"&gt;The credit facility led by IFC and Rabobank will be used to finance part of the project for the new thermoelectric generation unit at the S&amp;atilde;o Martinho Plant, which will expand the company&amp;rsquo;s generation of clean, renewable energy by around 20%, as well as its investments in renewing sugarcane fields using innovative new farming practices. The credit facility comprises US$ 55 million in funds from the IFC, with a term of 12 years, and US$ 45 million from Rabobank.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style="text-align: justify;"&gt;Part of the funding operation brings an innovative development in Brazilian agribusiness: green credit based on Green Loan Principles (GLP), making this the first green loan in Brazil&amp;rsquo;s sugar and ethanol industry. The goal of these principles is to create green credit structures that adopt high social and environmental standards and guidelines, incorporate solid methodologies and foster relations marked by ethical conduct. This portion of the facility will be used to conclude S&amp;atilde;o Martinho&amp;rsquo;s cogeneration expansion project, which involves replacing boilers and generators with lower-capacity, higher-efficiency equipment. This includes the use of regenerative cycle technology which, combined with the adoption of fluidized bed boilers, increases the amount of surplus power offered for sale to third parties by approximately 210 GWh each crop year, avoiding GHG emissions of 85,000 tons annually compared to the use of natural gas for power generation.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style="text-align: justify;"&gt;The project to expand clean and renewable energy generation not only will improve Brazil&amp;rsquo;s energy profile, but also produce enough electricity to power 46,000 homes using the same amount of bagasse currently consumed, while improving operational safety by automating processes and reducing annual emissions of particulates by around 300 tons and of nitrogen oxides (NOx) by 4 tons The investments in renewing S&amp;atilde;o Martinho&amp;rsquo;s sugarcane fields will draw on smart farming technologies, which including maximizing the use of organic fertilizers, adopting localized soil preparation techniques (reducing by fivefold GHG emissions compared to conventional techniques), recycling nutrients and using real-time imaging to accompany plant development.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style="text-align: justify;"&gt;These initiatives reinforce S&amp;atilde;o Martinho&amp;rsquo;s commitment as a leader in sustainability and ESG practices, while helping to develop and diversify Brazil&amp;rsquo;s energy profile, in line with the commitments undertook by the country in the Paris Climate Accord to reduce its GHG emissions by 43% between 2005 and 2030.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&amp;ldquo;These investments will expand S&amp;atilde;o Martinho&amp;rsquo;s power generation by around 20% and improve the country&amp;rsquo;s energy profile, especially during the period of the crop year coinciding with the dry season in the country&amp;rsquo;s Center-South production region. We also are planning acquisitions of equipment from regional companies that will create some 400 new jobs directly and indirectly, while supporting local economic development,&amp;rdquo; said S&amp;atilde;o Martinho CFO Felipe Vicchiato.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style="text-align: justify;"&gt;The nonconvertible infrastructure bonds were placed with a term of 10 years and amortizations in the 6&lt;sup&gt;th&lt;/sup&gt;, 7&lt;sup&gt;th&lt;/sup&gt;, 8&lt;sup&gt;th&lt;/sup&gt;, 9&lt;sup&gt;th&lt;/sup&gt; and 10&lt;sup&gt;th&lt;/sup&gt; years. The proceeds will be used to finance part of the corn ethanol plant attached to the Boa Vista Plant and for maintaining, adapting and modernizing the plant&amp;rsquo;s operations involving sugarcane planting, intercrop maintenance, crop treatments, equipment and replacement parts, as well as investments in operational safety at industrial units.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style="text-align: justify;"&gt;The bond issue was subjected to a Second Party Opinion (SPO) by Sitawi, which attested to its compliance with the Green Bond Principles (GBP)&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt;, the Climate Bonds Standards&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt; and other internationally recognized sustainability standards. According to the opinion, the investment will contribute to the Sustainable Development Goals (SDG 7) and to Brazil&amp;rsquo;s targets under the Paris Accord.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style="text-align: justify;"&gt;Other ESG highlights of the corn ethanol project include:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li style="text-align: justify;"&gt;creating around 1,400 direct and indirect jobs;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style="text-align: justify;"&gt;using cane bagasse as an energy source, making plants less dependent on the use of other fuels;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style="text-align: justify;"&gt;introducing innovative industrial technologies that consequently cause positive impacts on the development of the industry and of local communities;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style="text-align: justify;"&gt;reducing by 90%&amp;sup1; the GHG emissions generated by the production of ethanol compared to gasoline. The expansion in biofuel volume will avoid around 360,000 tons of CO&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt; emissions annually.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style="text-align: justify;"&gt;advancing the substitution of soymeal by Distiller&amp;rsquo;s Dried Grains with Solubles (DDGS), which are more nutritional and digestible and in turn leverage livestock production and reduce dependence on pastureland during dry periods.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;ldquo;These funding operations demonstrate to the market our financial solidity and put us in a strong position for accessing credit, like companies in other industries, such as pulp and paper, while expanding our exposure among different investor profiles,&amp;rdquo; said the CFO.&lt;/p&gt;

